			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The reason I didn't mention debuffing as a common primary role has a lot to do with class makeup, as well as typical positioning.
<br />

<br />
Debuffing generates a large amount of aggro. Mages are ill-equipped, compared to enchanters with runes or shamen/druids with higher HP, AC, and self-healing capabilities, to be the brunt of incoming aggro. I prefer the healer to be focused on the puller and the MT than worrying about me taking those first rounds. 
<br />

<br />
Additionally, it is my playstyle to "hang back" where I can see everything going on in the camp and take responsive action if I need to. (I generally play 1st-person view.) If I were debuffing, the aggro would tend to pull the mob too far.
<br />

<br />
All that said, when the group makeup is such that there is value in mage debuffs, I make sure the group knows that I am likely to be taking early aggro, adjust my position to much closer to the pull spot, and take a few whacks.
<br />

<br />
Pendant of Malosinia (VT) or especially Veil of Lost Hopes (Time) would change my approach drastically. However, both these pieces imply a mage generally much better equipped than most.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=568700" target="_blank" class="postlink">Sage Itchyban of Veeshan</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
